{
  "text": "In that case, one should expect that spikes generated by excitatory input would occur faster than rebound spikes, which usually have relatively long delays [CITATION_1] . Hence, DIN spikes during stimulus ramps one and three would be expected to occur later than spikes during stimulus ramps two and four (Fig 10A, vertical dotted lines) . Such systematic differences were not present in velocity-sensitive DINs [CITATION_2] . Therefore, a rebound mechanism is an unlikely explanation.",
